725394f-a.text:
51st Avenue, north side, east from Jackson Avenue, showing the types of buildings that prevailed in this section of Long Island City at the time when the Queens-Midtown Tunnel was cut through. The houses between the second telephone pole and the tree were later razed and on the site was erected the Service Building of the new tunnel.
November 17, 1938
New York City Tunnel Authority

10-20 - 10-26 51st Avenue, south side, east of Jackson Avenue, showing the factory of the Chilton Pen Company. The building was later torn down, together with the other buildings on the block, to make way for the construction of the Queens-Midtown Tunnel.

726936f-a.text:
10-10 Jackson Avenue, south side, between 51st Avenue and Vernon Boulevard. This building, as well as the others comprising the block, was razed to make way for the construction of the sub-level plaza of the Queens-Midtown Tunnel. This marks the exact site of the entrance to the tunnel, below street level.

November 22, 1938
New York City Tunnel Authority

726941f-a.text:
Jackson Avenue, south side, at 51st Avenue. These buildings were later razed and the area made part of the sunken plaza of the Queens-Midtown Tunnel. The entrance to the tunnel is below the street level on the exact site of these houses.

November 22, 1938

New York City Tunnel Authority

726947f-a.text:
Jackson Avenue, south side, west from 51st Avenue to Vernon Boulevard, showing the group of buildings that were later razed and on whose site was constructed the entrance to the Queens-Midtown Tunnel. The tall structure is the Clay Building to the right which is the Vernon Boulevard viaduct over the Long Island Railroad yards.

November 17, 1938

New York City Tunnel Authority
